==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gull
<hw>Gull</hw> <pr>(g⟦ucr⟧l)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Gulled</conjf> <pr>(g⟦ucr⟧ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Gulling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Prob. fr.
<ets>gull</ets> the bird; but cf. OSw. <ets>gylla</ets> to deceive, D.
<ets>kullen</ets>, and E. <ets>cullibility</ets>.]</ety> <def>To
deceive; to cheat; to mislead; to trick; to defraud.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The rulgar, <qex>gulled</qex> into rebellion, armed.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I'm not <qex>gulling</qex> him for the emperor's service.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gull</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Gull
<hw>Gull</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A cheating or cheat;
trick; fraud.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One easily cheated; a dupe.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gull</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Gull
<hw>Gull</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Of Celtic origin; cf. Corn.
<ets>gullan</ets>, W. <ets>gwylan</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>
<def>One of many species of long-winged sea birds of the genus
<gen>Larus</gen> and allied genera.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Among the best known American species are the herring
gull (<spn>Larus argentatus</spn>), the great black-backed gull (<spn>L.
murinus</spn>) the laughing gull (<spn>L. atricilla</spn>), and
Bonaparte's gull (<spn>L. Philadelphia</spn>). The common European gull
is <spn>Larus canus</spn>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Gull teaser</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the jager;
-- also applied to certain species of terns.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gullage</ent>⟦br⟧
